{{more footnotes|date=March 2013}} [[Image:Turkey ancient region map phrygia.gif|thumb|200px|'''Phrygia''' in '''yellow''', the area '''Gordoservon''' was located in]]
In records from [[Bithynia]] in the year 680, the city of '''Gordoservon''' or '''Gordoserbon''' ({{lang-el|Γορδόσερβον}}; [[Proto-Slavic]]: *''[[wikt:Appendix:Proto-Slavic/gordъ|Gordŭ]] [[wikt:Appendix:Proto-Slavic/sьrbъ|Sĭrbŭ]]''; [[Serbian language|Serbian]]: ''Гордосервон/Gordoservon, Гордосербон/Gordoserbon, Србоград/Srbograd, Град Срба/Grad Srba'' – "City of Serbs") was a [[Byzantine]] city inhabited by [[Serbs]]. The name is derived from the Serbs that [[Asia Minor Slavs|resettled in Asia Minor]] (in ca 649<ref name="google">{{cite book|title=Serbian Studies|author=North American Society for Serbian Studies|date=1995|issue=v. 9-10|publisher=North American Society for Serbian Studies|issn=0742-3330|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kXVpAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=2014-12-11}}</ref> or 667<ref name="google2">{{cite book|title=The Yugoslavs: the history of the Yugoslavs and their states to the creation of Yugoslavia|author=Kostelski, Z.|date=1952|publisher=Philosophical Library|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iuswAAAAIAAJ|accessdate=2014-12-11}}</ref>) by Byzantine Emperor [[Constans II (Byzantine Empire)|Constans II]] (641–668), who came from the areas "around the river [[Vardar]]". A "Bishop of Gordoservon" named Isidore is mentioned in 680/681, and the fact that this town was an episcopal seat gives ground to the thesis that it had a large Serbian population. The Serbs were recruited in large numbers into the [[Byzantine army]] especially under [[Justinian II]] in the 680s, until the defection of a 30,000-strong Serbian contingent led to the disastrous loss of the [[Battle of Sebastopolis]] in 692/693.
Around the year 1200&nbsp;AD this city is mentioned as '''Servochoria''' ({{lang-el|Σερβοχώρια}}, "Serbian habitations"). The city was situated where the [[Phrygia]]n kingdom once had been.
