{{Infobox person | name = Yevdokiya Nagrodskaya | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 1866 | birth_place = | death_date = 1930 | death_place = | nationality = | other_names = | occupation = [[Novelist]] | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = Novel - ''The Wrath of Dionysus'' }}
'''Yevdokiya Nagrodskaya''' ({{lang-rus|Евдокия Нагродская}}; 1866–1930), was a Russian novelist in [[fin-de-siècle]] [[Russia]] whose first novel was titled ''[[The Wrath of Dionysus]]''. Her [[debut novel]] was published in 1910 and explored the theme of her perception of "sexual identity and gender roles" of men and women in Russia. It was very popular in pre-revolutionary Russia among the middle-class people and was controversial.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.iupress.indiana.edu/product_info.php?products_id=21056|title=The Wrath of Dionysus|website=Indiana University Press|access-date=2016-04-25}}</ref> The novel was so popular that it was reprinted 10 times and translated into [[French language|French]], [[Italian language|Italian]] and [[German language|German]]. It was also made into a silent movie with erotic content.<ref name=New>{{Cite web|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/print/19970811/24140-a-new-view-of-russia.html|title=A New View of Russia|accessdate=22 April 2016|publisher= Publishersweekly.com}}</ref>{{Sfn|Nagrodskai︠a︡|McReynolds|1997|p=review}}
''The Wrath of Dionysus'' was translated into English only in 1997 at the initiative of [[Louise McReynolds]], a professor of history, in particular of Russian culture, at the [[University of Hawaii]]. It was published by the Indiana University Press<ref name=New/> and co-won the [[Heldt Prize]] in 1998.<ref name=":0" />
==Life== Yevdokiya Nagrodskaya was born as Evdokiia Apollonovna Golovacheva in Russia in 1866. Her mother was [[Avdotya Panaeva]], a writer of fiction and memoirs who co-edited the journal ''[[Sovremennik]]'' (1848–63), and her father was [[Apollon Golovachev]], a journalist.
She was later married and migrated to France after the publication of her novels. Later her novels were not popular in Russia.<ref name="High">{{Cite web|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G2-2591306914.html|title=Nagródskaia, Evdokiia (1866–1930)|publisher=Highbeam.com|accessdate=22 April 2016}}</ref>
Nagrodskaya died in 1930.<ref name="High" />
== ''The Wrath of Dionysus'' == In 1910, Nagrodskaya published her first novel, ''The Wrath of Dionysus.'' The book was described by Russia scholar [[Laura Engelstein]] as "boulevard fiction" in ''The Keys to Happiness: Sex and the Search for Modernity in Fin-de-Siècle Russia.''<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Keys to Happiness: Sex and the Search for Modernity in Fin-de-siècle Russia|last=Engelstein|first=Laura|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> In ''Libertinage in Russian Culture and Literature,'' Alexei Lalo stated that "[Nagródskaia] may have felt the need to represent the continuum of heterosexual and homosexual love and shifting gender identity more completely and insightfully than her contemporaries Zinovieva-Annibal or Verbitskaya did" and described the novel as "a more modern—and modernizing—literary phenomenon that many diverse researchers ... have taken it to be."<ref>{{Cite book|title=Libertinage in Russian Culture and Literature|last=Lalo|first=Alexei|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>
''The Wrath of Dionysus'' was highly popular and became a bestseller. After its success, she published more novels such as ''The Bronze Door'', ''The River of Times'', and ''The White Colonnade''.<ref name="New" />{{Sfn|Nagrodskai︠a︡|McReynolds|1997|p=review}}
''The Wrath of Dionysus'' was published in English in 1997 and was translated by Louise McReynolds, who said, "The Wrath of Dionysus is a rich blend of early cultural politics and explorations of sexual identity." She presents in this novel, set in [[Caucasus]], in the 20th-century middle-class Russia riddled with muddled conceptions about sex, her perception of gender difference by stating that [[effeminate]] men who show deep affection to their children are [[homosexual]], and women who are masculine in nature with independent thinking are [[lesbian]]; but both derive sexual pleasure from each other.<ref name="Kalfus">{{Cite web|last= Kalfus|first= Ken|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/12/14/bib/971214.rv115927.html|title= The Wrath Of Dionysus|date= 14 December 1997|accessdate=22 April 2016|publisher=New York Times}}</ref>
The English edition of the novel was reviewed by the ''[[Midwest Book Review]]'', who described it as an "outstanding edition," and by the ''[[Library Journal]]'', who said that it was "highly recommended for collections of Slavic literature as well as popular fiction."<ref name=":0" /> ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' wrote, "The themes of The Wrath of Dionysus sound so contemporary that it may surprise readers to find them in a Russian novel published more than 80 years ago."<ref name=":0" /> The ''[[Kirkus Reviews|Kirkus Review]]'' described the book as "well-known throughout Europe."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/evdokia-nagrodskaia/the-wrath-of-dionysus/|title=THE WRATH OF DIONYSUS by Evdokia Nagrodskaia {{!}} Kirkus Reviews|website=Kirkus Reviews|language=en-us|access-date=2016-04-25}}</ref>
